{
  "document_id": "prov-18",
  "title": "Proverbs 18",
  "type": "study-bible",
  "translation": "Oxford",
  "blocks": [
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-heading-19",
      "type": "heading",
      "text": "19"
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-2",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 2,
      "text": "A fool takes no pleasure in understanding, but only in expressing personal opinion."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-h1kj-3",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "2 : See 12.23; Eccl 10.3.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 18
      },
      "verse_start": 2,
      "verse_end": 2
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-3",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 3,
      "text": "When wickedness comes, contempt comes also; and with dishonor comes disgrace."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-h1kj-4",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "3 : See 11.2n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 18
      },
      "verse_start": 3,
      "verse_end": 3
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-4",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 4,
      "text": "The words of the mouth are deep waters; the fountain of wisdom is a gushing stream."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-h1kj-5",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "4 : , see 10.11n. denote quantity, cool refreshment, and mystery—even chaos (20.5; cf. Ps 64.6).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 18
      },
      "verse_start": 4,
      "verse_end": 4
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-5",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 5,
      "text": "It is not right to be partial to the guilty, or to subvert the innocent in judgment."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-h1kj-6",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "5 : , see 24.23–25n.; cf. 17.26.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 18
      },
      "verse_start": 5,
      "verse_end": 5
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-6",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 6,
      "text": "A fool's lips bring strife, and a fool's mouth invites a flogging."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-7",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 7,
      "text": "The mouths of fools are their ruin, and their lips a snare to themselves."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-8",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 8,
      "text": "The words of a whisperer are like delicious morsels; they go down into the inner parts of the body."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-h1kj-7",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "6–8 : Effects of foolish speech, see 10.13–14; 12.13; 13.3; 14.3,8.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 18
      },
      "verse_start": 6,
      "verse_end": 8
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-h1kj-8",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "8 : See 26.22. On as food, see 12.14n. , see 16.28n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 18
      },
      "verse_start": 8,
      "verse_end": 8
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-9",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 9,
      "text": "One who is slack in work is close kin to a vandal."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-h1kj-9",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "9 : , see 6.9–11n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 18
      },
      "verse_start": 9,
      "verse_end": 9
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-10",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 10,
      "text": "The name of the Lord is a strong tower; the righteous run into it and are safe."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-11",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 11,
      "text": "The wealth of the rich is their strong city; in their imagination it is like a high wall."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-h1kj-10",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "10–11 : A proverb pair that contrasts the certain security of the (e.g., Pss 20.2; 54.3; 61.3) to the unreliable security of wealth (cf. 10.15–16; 11.4; 28.11).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 18
      },
      "verse_start": 10,
      "verse_end": 11
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-12",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 12,
      "text": "Before destruction one's heart is haughty, but humility goes before honor."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-h1kj-11",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "12 : , see 11.2n. , see 3.7n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 18
      },
      "verse_start": 12,
      "verse_end": 12
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-13",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 13,
      "text": "If one gives answer before hearing, it is folly and shame."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-14",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 14,
      "text": "The human spirit will endure sickness; but a broken spirit—who can bear?"
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-h1kj-12",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "14 : See 17.22n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 18
      },
      "verse_start": 14,
      "verse_end": 14
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-15",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 15,
      "text": "An intelligent mind acquires knowledge, and the ear of the wise seeks knowledge."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-16",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 16,
      "text": "A gift opens doors; it gives access to the great."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-h1kj-13",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "16 : See 17.8n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 18
      },
      "verse_start": 16,
      "verse_end": 16
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-17",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 17,
      "text": "The one who first states a case seems right, until the other comes and cross-examines."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-18",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 18,
      "text": "Casting the lot puts an end to disputes and decides between powerful contenders."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-h1kj-14",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "17–18 : Warning to hear all sides of a dispute before making a decision. Some disputes may require lots to decide them (see 1.14n.), i.e., trusting divine guidance.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 18
      },
      "verse_start": 17,
      "verse_end": 18
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-19",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 19,
      "text": "An ally offended is stronger than a city; such quarreling is like the bars of a castle."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-h1kj-15",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "19 : , perhaps iron bars used to secure the gates (e.g., 1 Sam 23.7).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 18
      },
      "verse_start": 19,
      "verse_end": 19
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-20",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 20,
      "text": "From the fruit of the mouth one's stomach is satisfied; the yield of the lips brings satisfaction."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-21",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 21,
      "text": "Death and life are in the power of the tongue, and those who love it will eat its fruits."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-h1kj-16",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "20–21 : See v. 8n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 18
      },
      "verse_start": 20,
      "verse_end": 21
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-22",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 22,
      "text": "He who finds a wife finds a good thing, and obtains favor from the Lord."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-h1kj-17",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "22 : See 12.4n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 18
      },
      "verse_start": 22,
      "verse_end": 22
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-23",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 23,
      "text": "The poor use entreaties, but the rich answer roughly."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-h1kj-18",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "23 : Observation or condemnation of callousness to ; see 14.31n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 18
      },
      "verse_start": 23,
      "verse_end": 23
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-24",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 24,
      "text": "Some friends play at friendship but a true friend sticks closer than one's nearest kin."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-18-h1kj-1",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "10.1–22.16: The proverbs of Solomon. Comprised predominantly of two-line proverbs, the oldest section of Proverbs can be divided into 10.1–15.33, which features antithetical proverbs, and 16.1–22.16, which includes a mix of proverbial forms.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 18
      },
      "verse_start": 1,
      "verse_end": 24
    }
  ]
}